How Magnesium Boosts Your Immune System
Magnesium clearly has a profound impact on your overall health. But one aspect of its impact on the body that has spiked interest in researchers is the immune system. Magnesium, specifically magnesium chloride is shown to not just support the body’s immune system, but strengthen it. It can help stimulate and increase efficiency in combating illness and disease.

Without magnesium, studies have found your body’s natural immune responses can be negatively impacted. On the flip side, they have also shown that having sufficient amounts of magnesium in your system can boost natural immune responses and have some involvement in reducing inflammation, apoptosis, etc. Magnesium has also shown to play a role in oxidative stress, which can have a large negative impact on your immune system if not properly managed.

There’s still research that needs to be done in order to really place a finger on what it is that gives magnesium its fascinating effect on your immune system. column31: Is Facebook a publisher or a platform? The answer DOES actually matter...a lot. A "platform" is a service offered with no restrictions. People can use it how they please, and say or do anything with it. The owner of the platform is not legally liable for the way people use (or misuse) the service. An example would be people using a telephone service or email provider to discuss criminal activity -- neither the phone nor email companies would be liable, only the individuals involved. But a "publisher" is a different animal entirely. A publisher curates content and decides which views to present or allow. They ARE legally liable for what is shared on their platform. This would be like a newspaper or magazine, where writers are hired and even letters-to-the-editor are selected carefully. For years, Facebook has claimed to be a platform -- and enjoyed freedom from liability -- while shadow banning or outright removing content. They have tried to control the flow of speech and ideas by fact-checking people and hiding posts. This actually makes them a publisher. Facebook will soon have to decide if they actually believe in freedom of speech (and be a true platform) or if they will be a publisher (and lose their freedom from liability -- which will mean they will start kicking people off whom they deem "risky"). They are already preparing for this. Their Oct. 1 TOS update includes language that Facebook can remove content and users who place them at risk of liability. How much longer will any of us even be allowed here? Remains to be seen....

column31: The secret to cooking food your family actually wants to eat... I used to think cooking was complicated. And that soup only came in cans...honestly. 😳 Then I came across @westonaprice and learned about the benefits of eating less processed food & more real food (meat, eggs, raw milk, ferments, etc.) I seriously didn’t know my way around the kitchen. At. all. Dinner was often fish sticks & baby carrots, just to give you an idea. 🙄 But when I did start cooking—particularly meats from a local farm—to my surprise, meals started tasting amazing. It’s not that I was a stellar cook. I quickly discovered the secret to tasty meals that my family would drool over. The secret? QUALITY INGREDIENTS 😋 Meat from pastured animals doesn’t need a lot of embellishment, tbh. Case in point: these lamb chop lollipops I bought at a farmers market while at a NJ beach. I literally sautéed these briefly in some olive oil (at a low temp to avoid reaching the smoke point). I added some garlic powder, salt & pepper. And that was it. But🤩 WOW, these never-frozen chops were melt-in-your-mouth delish. We had these for breakfast yesterday along w/ some duck eggs over easy. 🍳 Everybody was thrilled! And so was I! So, my little suggestion? Buy the best quality food you can. Esp. meat! 🥩 Don’t worry about following complicated recipes. The meat itself will shine when it’s: - local - sustainably raised - hormone & antibiotic free And your family will likely beg for more. 😁 Subscribe to the Wise Traditions podcast to learn more about this way of eating (& living)! A podcast with Joel Salatin comes out on Monday on just this subject. ☺️ And check out my IG story to see just how happy these chops made me. 😆

column36:
So last Friday night while I was carving and building a cake, I received a random text from one of my friends asking if I could feed a strangers baby. Was there ever a question? The baby's mother was having surgery and the baby is exclusively breastfed and refused a bottle. When the baby arrived you could tell she was hungry and exhausted and just needed some milk. I did what I hope any person would do for my child in a time of despair. I fed a strangers baby. I was so surprised by just how many people thought it was weird, or unnatural. They are boobs, they are meant to feed babies. Also, in case anyone forgot, they are mine, so I'm fairly certain I choose what happens with them. Regardless, I took an amazing photo tandem nursing these two babies together and it shows that hungry babies don't care, they just need to be fed.

column31: In the U.S., an estimated 12% to 38% of doctors’ prescriptions are for off-label uses (the prescription of a drug for a non-FDA-approved use). Although this practice has the potential for abuse, the president of the American College of Physicians says, “Just because something is an off-label use doesn’t mean it doesn’t work. And it doesn’t mean it’s inappropriate.” The issue of off-label prescribing has come up repeatedly for Covid-19 and was touched on indirectly in a mid-August interview with Dr. Anthony Fauci. Asked his opinion about two remedies reported as helpful for some Covid-19 patients: zinc supplements and an inhaled steroid that some physicians have prescribed to help distressed Covid-19 patients breathe, Fauci was instantly negative about both. He stated that many things “work in the test tube but don’t work in the body” and suggesting that, at best, the two remedies might occasionally be associated with a placebo effect. But clinical trials say otherwise. Are Fauci's negative opinions about potential Covid-19 therapies evidence-based or political?

column31: We get asked all the time if we make a weight loss supplement...and the answer is no. That's on purpose. We don't make a weight loss supplement. We'll never make a weight loss supplement. Why not? First of all, because people are great the way they are. They aren't worth "less" if the number on the scale is higher. They don't need to wait to embrace themselves or live their best lives until they achieve the right dress size. Embrace yourself and live now! Second, weight is not a good measure of health. People can be "thin" yet struggle in many ways, or "heavy" yet be fit and active. There's no way to know how healthy someone is just by looking at them. Third, if someone does need to lose weight for any reason, it's a complex issue. It's not because they're lazy or they just eat too much. Many people, especially women, eat as well as they can and exercise and still don't lose weight. Because it's a complex hormonal issue, possible toxicity, etc. We are happy to support you in feeling strong, having energy, and living your healthiest life. But we won't reduce you to a number on a scale.

column31: Friends, are you prepared for the Labor day weekend and the fireworks that accompany it, to keep your pet calm and safe? 🇺🇸 🐾🐾🍉🐕 Any effort you can implement now to minimize feelings of anxiety, stress, panic and fear is time well spent. Sadly, this is one of the holidays that is the busiest for shelters across the country as many dogs run away during the fireworks shows. When the bombs and cannons start going off, dogs do not understand and instantly go into a fight or flight mode. Many will jump through windows and doors and injure themselves or worse, trying to get away from the fireworks. "Firework holidays" are some of the worst times of the year for most dogs and their people, however, being prepared ahead of time can lessen stress for both of you 🌻 Here is my article with 13 great tips, here is a sneak peak .. 1. Exercise Your Dog Before the Fireworks Start! A tired dog is a calm dog. 2. Stay Home. Offering them safety and comfort and supervision will greatly help keep them calm and sage. 3. Keep Calm. The owner’s frame of mind is very influential to dogs, and it’s been shown that anxious dog owners are more prone to have dogs that develop noise phobia and other anxieties. Your dog will respond and react to your nonverbal cues. If you are nervous, uncomfortable, irritated or tense when you hear fireworks your dog will sense that and respond accordingly. 4. Drown Out the Sound. I've created a “bunker” for Tuck, my German Shepherd in our basement. It has a very large kennel with nice thick soft blankets and I have a radio on and a nice fan and anti-stress oils being diffused. 5.🔥🐾 PROTIP for all year round concerns and support: Therapeutic (not novelty) Essential Oils to the Rescue. Aromatherapy works very well for animals, I use 3-4 drops of lavender, stress away and/or peace and calming along his spine (head to tail), he relaxes unbelievably within 5 minutes. 💦💧I can get you your health boosting starter kit of 12 organic supportive oils + a gorgeous home diffuser and the kit contains lavender, stress away and peace and calming, everything you need for a calmer relaxed pet (and you) ... for $28 with zero % interest - to give you relief now. 6. CBD oil can be amazing to support their ECS. Supporting the ECS helps with balancing the autonomic nervous system, the fight or flight components and keeping your dog calm and having restful deep sleep. 7. Real Food Nutrition. Your dogs nervous system, neurology and brain function is dependent on the quality of nutrients you are feeding him/her. Their ancestral diet of real food such as beef, liver, eggs, sardines and a small amount of greens will help to rebuild, repair and boost their immunity, in turn helping them stay balanced in regards to their autonomic nervous system, the flight or flight. 8. Respect Your Dog’s Fear. Allow your dog to hide if he/she feels more comfortable in its crate or under a bed. 9. Provide a Distraction. Break out your dog’s favorite healthy treats, play a game, or give it some extra cuddle time, this can really help reassure you pet that everything will be okay an that they are safe. 10. Consider Boarding. If you are going to be out for the day/night and your dog has a daycare he just loves, consider leaving him/her there with other dog buddies and a staff to keep an eye on him/her. Plus, many day cares are so well-insulated, and there is so much noise from other dogs barking, that your dog may not even hear the fireworks on the big night. 11. Try a Thunder Shirt. There are many different brands on the market including the Thunder Shirt and the Anxiety Wrap, which were tested by Tufts University and is approved by them to diminish signs of fear in dogs during thunderstorms. 12. If Absolutely Necessary, Don't Rule out Calming Medication. I'm not one for medication unless absolutely necessary due to the side effects, but in this case, however, if your dog really freaks out you can ask your vet for a mild sedative, but try the other things before medicating your dog. 13. Be Prepared. All these tips will help you to provide safety and comfort to your best friend ..ahead of time to offer you and them the best weekend possible. column31: Published on July 9 by WHO: "One experimental study quantified the amount of droplets of various sizes that remain airborne during normal speech. However, the authors acknowledge that this relies on the independent action hypothesis, which has not been validated for humans and SARS-CoV-2.(18) Another recent experimental model found that healthy individuals can produce aerosols through coughing and talking (19), and another model suggested high variability between individuals in terms of particle emission rates during speech, with increased rates correlated with increased amplitude of vocalization.(20) To date, transmission of SARS-CoV-2 by this type of aerosol route has not been demonstrated..." Catch that? That whole theory that just by breathing and talking, we're spreading aerosols that could give others the virus DOESN'T HAPPEN. Or at least has never been proven to happen. column31: The New York Times said this morning that out of 183,000 COVID deaths, 145,000 didn't have to happen. They blamed this difference on "poor response." We have a very different perspective on that. NYT actually acknowledges in this article that the US had some of the worst health outcomes prior to COVID, but glosses over it, and notes that as a "rich" country with "vast" capabilities in (allopathic) medicine, we should have done well, or at least a bit better than average. Unfortunately, that's a fantasy. The very issues where we have the worst health outcomes (heart disease, diabetes, cancer) were also the strongest predictors of severe or fatal COVID cases. We built a system over the last few decades where more and more people are dealing with chronic health issues, and where they are unable to get real, non-allopathic help for them. (Many do not know non-allopathic options exist; and if they do, they often cannot access them or afford them.) We created a highly susceptible population. And now we're blaming the short-term response for this outcome? No, this was a long time in the making. Healthy people had a much lower risk of severe or fatal disease than those who weren't. Had our population been healthier, the response would not have mattered so much. We need to take a good, hard look at what we're doing here. On our over-reliance on allopathy. On our continued poor outcomes. On key metrics (like maternal mortality) that keep getting WORSE. We simply could not handle something like COVID in the state our country was in. Blaming it on anything other than the poor system we've built is short-sighted and will never solve the problems. Are we ready to have this conversation yet...and find real solutions?
